@Node "Loc_Init" "Locator.libary/Lor_Init()"

   NAME
    Loc_Init()  -- Init Locator Library Stuff. (V1)


   SYNOPSIS
    result := Loc_Init()

    ULONG  Loc_Init( void );
    D0

   FUNCTION
    This routine initializes Locator library.


   INPUTS

   RESULTS
    result          - This could be:
                        TRUE  =  CORRECT initialization.
                        FALSE =  INCORRECT init.  (Should NEVER happen!)


   NOTES
    Call this routine EXACTLY ONCE at startup!

   SEE ALSO
    @{" Loc_Dispose()   " LINK "Loc_Dispose"}

   BUGS

@EndNode

@Node "Loc_Dispose" "Locator.libary/Loc_Dispose()"

   NAME
    Loc_Dispose()    -- This command closes all Locator.library stuff.

   SYNOPSIS
    Loc_Dispose()

    VOID Loc_Dispose( void );

   FUNCTION
    Use this function to free everything before closing the library.

   INPUTS

   RESULTS

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO
    @{" Loc_Init() " LINK "Loc_Init"}

   BUGS

@EndNode

@Node "Loc_Open" "Locator.libary/Loc_Open()"

   NAME
    Loc_Open()  -- Open and read a Locator catalog file. (V1)


   SYNOPSIS
    result = Loc_Open(handler, filename)

    ULONG  = Loc_Open(locator_handler *, CHAR *)
    D0                 A0                D0


   FUNCTION
    This is one of the most important commands.
    Call this function to open up a Locator file and load up all its
    contents into memory.


   INPUTS
    handler         a PTR to a _VALID_ locator_handler.

    fname           Locator catalog's filename.

   RESULTS
    result          0 = No errors occurred
                   <0 = Errors occurred



   NOTES
    It is possible to re-use an handler without close it before Open()
    another catalog. In this case, the catalog currently handled by
    the handler will be closed automagically.


   SEE ALSO
    @{" Loc_Close()        " LINK "Loc_Close"}
    @{" Loc_Message()      " LINK "Loc_Message"}
    @{" Loc_AllocHandler() " LINK "Loc_AllocHandler"}
    @{" ERROR TABLE        " LINK "error_table"}

   BUGS

@EndNode

@Node "Loc_Close" "Locator.libary/Loc_Close()"

   NAME
    Loc_Close()      -- Closes a catalog opened with Open(). (V1)


   SYNOPSIS
    Loc_Close(handle)

    VOID Loc_Close(locator_handler *)
                   A1

   FUNCTION
    This function closes a catalog previously opened by the Loc_Open()
    function.

   INPUTS
    handle          -  PTR to a valid locator_handler.

   RESULTS

   NOTES
    You can pass a NIL pointer to this function safely.

   SEE ALSO
    @{" Loc_Open() " LINK "Loc_Open"}

   BUGS

@EndNode

@Node "Loc_AllocHandler" "Locator.libary/Loc_AllocHandler()"

   NAME
    Loc_AllocHandler()   -- Allocates a valid Locator Handler. (V1)

   SYNOPSIS
    handler             = Loc_AllocHandler(     )

    locator_handler *                       VOID
    D0

   FUNCTION
    This command allocates a valid Locator Handler for you.

   INPUTS

   RESULTS
    handler             -- A valid Locator Handler is returned.
                           Check it against NIL (failure) which could only
                           happen due to low memory problems.

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO
    @{" Loc_FreeHandler() " LINK "Loc_FreeHandler"}

   BUGS

@EndNode

@Node "Loc_FreeHandler" "Locator.libary/Loc_FreeHandler()"

   NAME
    Loc_FreeHandler()   -- Release all the memory allocated by
                           the handler. (V1)

   SYNOPSIS
    Loc_GetValue(handler)

    VOID         locator_handler *
                 D0

   FUNCTION
    This command will release all memory allocated by the handler.
    If the handler you wish to free is in use (eg. still holding data
    stored by a Loc_Open()) it will completely be freed up before freeing the
    handler.

    The handler will not be valid anymore.

   INPUTS
    handler      -- PTR to locator_handler.

   RESULTS

   NOTES
    *   You can safely pass a NIL handler to this command.

    *   The handler freed cannot be reused (it is nuked to NIL). So if you
        want to re use an handler use the Loc_Close command instead of
        this one.

    *   Remeber to ALWAYS Loc_FreeHandler() any handler before exiting.

   SEE ALSO
    @{" Loc_Close()        " LINK "Loc_Close"}
    @{" Loc_AllocHandler() " LINK "Loc_AllocHandler"}

   BUGS

@EndNode

@Node "Loc_Message" "Locator.libary/Loc_Message()"

   NAME
    Loc_Message()   -- Return the message desired. (V1)

   SYNOPSIS
    Loc_Message(handler, message_number, default_message)

    msg = Loc_Message(handler,           message_number, default_message)
    CHAR *            locator_handler *, ULONG           CHAR *
    DO                A0                 D1              D0

   FUNCTION
    This routine returns the desired message string.

   INPUTS
    handler         -- PTR to a _valid_ locator_handler

    message_number  -- Number of the message to get.

    default_message -- Default Message string. This string will be returned
                       when desired message_number does not exist.


   RESULTS
    msg             -- A CHAR * containing the desired string.

   NOTES
    If the Loc_Message fails, the default_message defined will be returned.

   SEE ALSO

   BUGS
@EndNode

@node "OverView" "Locator.libary/Overview"

    Locator.libary V1.00 - (C)1995 By Fabio Rotondo

    *** NOTE: This library is dedicated to all Amiga fanatics around the  ***
    ***       world. Please, continue developing for this machine now and ***
    ***       forever. All Amiga community needs you. (And keep prices    ***
    ***       as low as possible!! ;)                                     ***

                      *** AMIGA. Feel The Power !!! ***

    This is a small library I have written to allows programs localization
    also on OS2.0.

    This is not intended to be a Locale.library replacement: my library is
    not so powerful neither it will become so... it is just intended as a
    "temporarely bridge" solution until everyone will become an happy
    OS3.0+ user.

    Anyway, I do intend to continue developing this library, so if you want
    any new feature... just write me and we will sort things out!

    Please note: This library is "Soft"-Ware! See @{" COPYRIGHT " LINK "Copyright"}

    See @{" Author's Infos " LINK "author"} for my addresses.

@endnode

